oc:kn_08f11d54 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting a logo type for a client or project" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Match logo type to brand maturity and recognition: wordmarks for established brands with distinctive names, pictorial marks for globally recognized brands, combination marks for new brands needing versatility." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Using a pictorial mark without brand equity leaves the logo unrecognizable; combination marks provide flexibility for unknown brands to build recognition." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_41ec56f4 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing a visual style direction for a logo" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use the Style Selection Matrix to pair brand industry with appropriate aesthetic: Tech → Minimalist/Abstract, Fashion → Wordmark/Luxury, Restaurant → Mascot/Badge, Law → Wordmark/Emblem." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Industry alignment ensures the logo communicates the right brand attributes to the target audience." .

oc:kn_5140fa86 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When considering emblem-style logos" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Do not use emblems for applications requiring small-scale reproduction without testing scalability first — their enclosed badge/seal structure often loses detail at small sizes." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Emblems explicitly have known scalability challenges; they work best for traditional organizations at larger display sizes." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_70b37067 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before finalizing any logo design" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Every logo must pass the Scalability Checklist: recognizable at 16x16px, clear at business card size, works in single color, maintains clarity in black/white, no tiny details that vanish when scaled down." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Logos appear across contexts from favicons to billboards; failure at small sizes or in monochrome destroys brand utility." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_f552a7e1 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When applying an aesthetic style to a logo" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Limit minimalist logos to 1-2 colors with high white space; luxury logos should use gold/black/white with thin serifs or sophisticated sans-serifs; gradient/modern styles suit digital-native brands." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Color palette and typography choices must reinforce the aesthetic intent or the style becomes inconsistent." .

